[Some clarifications should be mentioned here. 1st, Nigeria did not confirm an AFP case due to cVDPV2 infection this past week, but rather identified a positive environmental sample in Kwara state. 2nd, the Philippines DOH and WHO have confirmed 2 cVDPV2-associated AFP cases in the Philippines: 1 in Lanao del Sur in the southern part of the Philippines and the other in Laguna province approximately 100 km [62 mi] to the south of the Manila metro area. (see Poliomyelitis update (75): Philippines, WHO, no new confirmed cases 20190925.6694087). The media is reflecting the heightened awareness ongoing in the Philippines with almost daily reports of new suspected cases pending laboratory results. As a reminder, the majority of AFP cases investigated in most countries end up classified as non-poliovirus infection associated, therefore, seeing these reports in the local media serves as a sign there is ongoing heightened AFP surveillance and an interest on the part of the general population towards the importance of the AFP surveillance.

This year (2019) to date, Pakistan has reported 66 cases of WPV1-associated polio, the highest annual report since 2014 when it had reported 306 cases (data available at https://drive.google.com/file/d/1LGiJJvFwjHhQq_XWWLwrqgezQjAnxaSo/view page 4). The same applies to the global totals. As of 25 Sep 2019, there have been a total of 82 confirmed cases of WPV1-associated polio this year [2019], the highest reported since 2014 when there were 359 cases confirmed. Similarly, 2019 is seeing the highest number of countries reporting cVDPV-associated cases (same link page 5) with 20 countries confirming cVDPV-associated polio cases since 1 Jan 2019.

As done in previous posts, to visualize all of this activity, I am putting links to HealthMap/ProMED-mail maps of countries with poliovirus activity during the past 12 months below. The size of the list remains impressive, now with 20 countries: 12 in Africa, 5 in Asia, and 3 in the Western Pacific.

